03882nam a22006015i 9780300183436DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20122012ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001834367 a10.12987/97803001834362doi  a(DE-B1597)484755  a(OCoLC)1024051704  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aDC33.4b.K47 2012eb 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a9441 aKete, Kathleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Way for Genius :bThe Irish Aristocracy in the Seventeenth Century /cKathleen Kete. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b1 b-w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Aspiring Self in France from the Old Regime to the New -- t2. Genius, Madame de Staël, and the Soul of Prodigious Success -- t3. Vocation, Stendhal, and the Art of Living Ethically -- t4. Destiny, Cuvier, and Post-Revolutionary Politics -- t5. Friendship Matters; Arguments from Egypt; Coda on Napoleon -- t6. Ambition in Post-Revolutionary Lives -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamining the lives and works of three iconic personalities -Germaine de Staël , Stendhal, and Georges Cuvier-Kathleen Kete creates a groundbreaking cultural history of ambition in post-Revolutionary France. While in the old regime the traditionalist view of ambition prevailed-that is, ambition as morally wrong unless subsumed into a corporate whole-the new regime was marked by a rising tide of competitive individualism. Greater opportunities for personal advancement, however, were shadowed by lingering doubts about the moral value of ambition.Kete identifies three strategies used to overcome the ethical “burden” of ambition : romantic genius (Staël ), secular vocation (Stendhal), and post-mythic destiny (Cuvier). In each case, success would seem to be driven by forces outside one’s control. She concludes by examining the still relevant (and still unresolved) conundrum of the relationship of individual desires to community needs, which she identifies as a defining characteristic of the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmbitionxSocial aspectszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aAmbitionxSocial aspectszFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aIndividualityzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aIndividualityzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aSelfzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aSelfzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030017482340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018343640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300183436423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300183436/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY